<DOC><DOCNO> AP900608-0271 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-90 1914EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-BusinessHighlights     06-08 0799</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0833</SECOND><DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ames Department Stores Inc., trying tojettison unprofitable operations, announced plans to close 221stores and lay off about 17,500 employees as it struggles to emergefrom bankruptcy protection.   The closings, which represent nearly a third of Ames' 679 storesnationwide, must be approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in NewYork, where the nation's fourth largest retailer filed forprotection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the federalbankrutpcy laws on April 25.   If the court approves, the company said Friday it plans to closethe stores in August or September after conducting inventoryliquidation sales.</TEXT><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu said he would not givein to a key U.S. trade demand that Japan specify targets forboosting its public works spending, a hoped-for wedge in opening themarket here to more foreign business.   Kaifu's tough stand Friday, coming a day after a tradebreakthrough in which Japan accepted U.S. technology as acellular-phone standard, suggests the government intends to assertitself despite heavy pressure for economic reform.   Japan agreed in April to increase public spending as part of anunprecedented pact to reduce its $49 billion trade surplus with theUnited States by attacking trade barriers. The prime minister hascome under harsh criticism in Parliament for bowing to U.S. demands.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   McDonald's Corp. said it would post completenutritional information _ including fat and sodium levels _ on allof its products at its restaurants this summer.   Terri Capatosto, a spokeswoman for the nation's biggest fast-foodrestaurant chain, said Friday the move was intended as a conveniencefor McDonald's customers, not as a response to a recent ad campaignattacking the nutritional value of the company's food.</TEXT><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastern Airlines has for the first time recalledpilots who stayed off the job until the end of the Air Line PilotsAssocation strike, the company said.   They will be among 90 pilots called back to handle increasedsummer schedules and a planned expansion of Atlanta routes, airlinespokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said Friday.</TEXT><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Texas Instruments Inc. and General Dynamics Corp.,a pair of major defense contractors, plan to lay off almost 2,000people in Texas because of anticipated military budget cutbacks.   Texas Instruments said Friday it will trim its Defense Systems andamp;Electronics Group by about 1,000 employees in the next year. Theannouncement came one day after General Dynamics announced plannedcuts of 500 to 800 people over the next few months at its Fort Worthdivision.</TEXT><DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Cardiac pacemaker giant Medtronic Inc. agreedto buy Bio-Medicus Inc. for $190 million in a bid to diversify itsline of cardiovascular medical devices.   The two biotechnology companies settled Friday on a stock swapworth $25 a share to Bio-Medicus shareholders, but the value andstock exchange ratio could change based on fluctuations inMedtronic's stock price.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Texas businessman stung in a federalcrackdown on child labor law violations cautioned Congress againstletting ``governmental paternalism'' ruin worthwhile workopportunities for youngsters.   Donald Farrell said Friday that jobs like those he provides giveyoungsters, especially those from unstable homes, a chance to earnmoney, experience and self-respect. His Dallas business is underinvestigation for allegedly letting nearly 300 children illegallysell newspaper subscriptions at night.</TEXT><DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush told pork producers thathis administration continues to push for including all agriculturalproducts in a new international trade accord, despite stiffresistance from Europe.   Also Friday, leaders of the swine industry announced an alliancewith colleagues in Canada and Mexico to attack barriers to sales oftheir products overseas and ``provide ammunition'' to U.S.negotiators at the Uruguay Round of talks under the GeneralAgreement on Tariffs and Trade.</TEXT><DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Cypress Semiconductor Corp. said it plansto make computer chips and other electronic devices for the SovietUnion in a unique licensing agreement that will give the companySoviet chip-making technologies.   Cypress said Friday it signed a letter of intent with theInternational Center for Informatics and Electronics of Moscow,which has officials touring the Silicon Valley as part of a 10-day``Silicon Summit.''</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market closed out its first losing week since Aprilwith a broad decline Friday. The Dow Jones industrial averagedropped 34.95 to 2,862.38, finishing the week with a net loss of38.59 points.   Gold prices finished a sluggish week higher and the dollar wasstronger against major currencies.   Bond prices dipped in light trading.   Cocoa futures prices were sharply lower; grain and soybeans werelower; livestock and pork futures mixed; precious metals were mixedand energy futures were higher.</TEXT></DOC>